comment_data.body:
@iio7 I know you tried zeertzjq's `FileChangedShell` autocommand already, but in the docs it says that that autocommand is only triggered after 1) executing a shell command, 2) using `:checktime`, or 3) after a `FocusGained` event.

I'm curious if *maybe* the `FileChangedShell` approach didn't work because it simply wasn't being fired. Just as a test, could you try running `:checktime` just before `:write`? You could maybe even modify your write mapping (assuming you have one) to `<Cmd>checktime<Bar>write<CR>`.

Anyway, I don't know if that will work, it's just something I noticed when reading through your issue.

I am not familiar with the source code of Vim/Neovim, but isn't all it would take to expand this conditional to check for a user setting like `noow` (No Overwrite Warning).

```
    /*
     * Check if the timestamp hasn't changed since reading the file.
     */
    if (overwriting) {
      retval = check_mtime(buf, &file_info_old);
      if (retval == FAIL) {
        goto fail;
      }
    }
```
